		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />You can go high tech and get one of these newer NVRAMs that have a buit-in battery. Basically you get one of the NVRAMs designed for real-time clocks that also has ab built-in battery, they are cheap and have 64x4 (32 byte) which can be had for under $3. I see some 1Kx8 and larger parts, but I didn't see any that large with a built-in battery.
<br />
<br />Is it necessary to use 1980s NVRAM technology for a 1980s console, or can we adapt some modern that is 5V capable. because it's hardly worth the cost to put bidirectional line drivers on it if you want to save money by buying 3V parts.
<br />
<br />has anyone tried the Catalyst Semiconductors NV SRAMs? like CAT22C10L-20 (18DIP) . Intersil X20C04 series (28DIP) can be had pretty cheap too. Dallas DS12xx are common enough to find used, but those need batteries but can be really big (32Kx8).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


